<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,820,1094]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,887,914]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Comment</emphasis>
. This species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[589,665,887,913]" name="Eritrea" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Eritrea</collectingCountry>
only. The 
<typeStatus box="[782,830,888,914]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
deposition is unknown. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lehtinen, P. T." box="[1099,1279,887,914]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="199 - 468" refId="ref5910" refString="Lehtinen, P. T. (1967) Classification of the cribellate spiders and some allied families, with notes on the evolution of the suborder Araneomorpha. Annales Zoologici Fennici, 4, 199 - 468." type="journal article" year="1967">Lehtinen (1967)</bibRefCitation>
supposed that it is a member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehtinen" authorityYear="1967" box="[387,535,923,949]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Titanoecidae</taxonomicName>
. Judging from the schematic figure of the epigyne, an abdomen lacking a pattern and its size it could be 
<taxonomicName authority="(Thorell, 1878)" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1878" baseAuthorityName="Thorell" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[419,809,959,986]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Pandava" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laminata">
<emphasis box="[419,627,960,986]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Pandava laminata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thorell, T." box="[643,800,959,986]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 317" refId="ref6974" refString="Thorell, T. (1878 b) Studi sui ragni Malesi e Papuani. II. Ragni di Amboina raccolti Prof. O. Beccari. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova, 13, 1 - 317." type="journal article" year="1878">Thorell, 1878</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehtinen" authorityYear="1967" box="[825,976,959,986]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Titanoecidae</taxonomicName>
), a species known from this region. The epigyne illustrated by L. Koch is rather more similar to that in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1874" box="[864,953,996,1021]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Nurscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[864,953,996,1021]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Nurscia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and particularly to 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon, 1874" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1874" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Nurscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albosignata">
<emphasis box="[1182,1348,996,1022]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">N. albosignata</emphasis>
Simon, 1874
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lucas, 1846)" authorityName="Lucas" authorityYear="1846" baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[263,618,1031,1058]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Nurscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">
<emphasis box="[263,451,1032,1058]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">N. albomaculata</emphasis>
(Lucas, 1846)
</taxonomicName>
, but unlike in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. Koch" authorityYear="1875" box="[781,877,1032,1058]" class="Arachnida" family="Amaurobiidae" genus="Amaurobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">
<emphasis box="[781,877,1032,1058]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">A. tristis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1874" box="[1041,1130,1032,1057]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Nurscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1041,1130,1032,1057]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Nurscia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have an abdominal pattern formed by a series of white paired spots. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[612,862,1068,1094]" class="Arachnida" family="Titanoecidae" genus="Nurscia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">
<emphasis box="[612,862,1068,1094]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="54">Nurscia albomaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from Northern Africa (Bonnet 1959).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
